      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seattle"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The city’s first library opened in 1891 in a Henry Yesler mansion, becoming a historic cultural hub.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        6
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seattle"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "Seattle’s iconic light rail, the 1 Line, began service in 2009, linking downtown to Sea‑Tac Airport.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        25
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seattle"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "The world’s largest tunnel boring machine, Bertha, was commissioned for the underwater tunnel project under Puget Sound.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        24
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seattle"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Seattle hosts four major professional sports teams, including the NFL Seahawks, MLB Mariners, NHL Kraken, and MLS Sounders.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
